p://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/22/02 1:08:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Prelimnary results from Orion test program</span><hr size=1> BTW, I'm brp13 from the other board. For those of you who don't know who I am still, well, sorry... If you remember my about my simulator, feel free to skip the rest of this paragraph. I've been trying to build a simulator to test some of the nastier parts of Orion, such as EMP, fallout, what happens if several bombs fail, etc. All in all I seem to be getting pretty close. <br>
<br>
Okay, I've finally got the program to work. And it seems to work great. I used several figures from the book Project Orion that is about to be published, namely it uses 800 bombs to get into orbit. was trying to figure out the exact time between bursts, if it could be done. I realized that the figures they had were not even optimal, so I changed the time between bursts to the most optimal setting, and hopefully it's not that far off... I guestamated each bomb uses about 80,000,000 newtons of force. I used metric tons instead of conventional, all my calculations have been done with metric...<br>
<br>
The first test I ran was what happens if bombs fail. Well, the good news is, unless more than 10% of them fail, it will make it outside of the earth in it's allocated 800 bombs to do so. And it would take bad luck for it to crash, more than 20% of the bombs would have to fail. Nuclear bombs are at least 99% accurate. So I set the failed bomb level down to 1% for the rest of my testing, which probably doesn't mean that much.<br>
<br>
EMP was quite a challenge. At first I was going to try to do something really cool. Unfortunately, it wouldn't work... So I used known figures for 1 Megaton bombs, ran tests on them until they were calibrated to the levels of destruction I wanted, then took the number and divided by 50. In other words, I was looking for a number that would give a destruction rating of 100 for several hundred miles. Higher than 100 is much worse. After I had that, I divided that number by 50 for the bombs that were 1/50th the size of a megaton bomb. Running this through my simulator, I came to the conclusion that about 250 km. would be effected, or about 150 miles. But I'm still trying to verify that, as well as make the simulator more accurate. 150 miles is acceptable, but that assumes that my initial figures were correct, and they may not have been. <br>
<br>
The next step on my list is to store all of the statistics for launches. If anyone wants my program as is, email me, and I'll be glad to send a copy and explain a bit more. The source I'm holding until I've presented my project. Anyone have any questions/comments? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/22/02 1:14:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  More that I forgot...</span><hr size=1> Okay, here's a bit more of the more technical reports. I have accounted for changes in gravity, bombs failing, somewhat to the curvature of the earth, but not entirely. I have accounted for change in mass of the spacecraft.<br>
<br>
I have not accounted for curvature in determining EMP in the middle ranges, but that shouldn't matter too much... I have not accounted for bombs changing in size, but I think they cancel each other out to a degree.<br>
<br>
I have assumed that EMP strength is linearly proportional, and that the pusher plate will work. I assumed each bomb massed 1 metric ton.<br>
<br>
I have yet to test fallout, any kind of accounting for radiation in the magnetic belts, and several other factors which I may or may not test.<br>
<br>
Again, comments are welcome. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 374<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 10:47:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: More that I forgot...</span><hr size=1> I remember reading somewhere that Orion would have enough power to<br>
climb straight up from the Earth into space, unlike conventional<br>
rockets that follow the Earth's curvature... of course this approach<br>
is usefull for reducing the amount of area affected by fallout.  After<br>
a predetermined altitude was reached the Orion would rotate and pulse<br>
to attain orbital velocity.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 11:36:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: More that I forgot...</span><hr size=1> Why does Orion even need to orbit? Why not just take straight off? Maybe an eliptical orbit to spare the earth of mroe fallout, but I don't know what else... The curvature I was talking about only is in relation to EMP. I've said a point 1000 miles away from ground 0 has the same EMP as a point at ground zero, on the ground, so long as the point 1000 miles away is in the line of sight. Does that make sense? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 376<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/23/02 2:26:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: More that I forgot...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Why does Orion even need to orbit?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I guess it depends on the mission profile.  If it needed <br>
to deliver a payload to orbit, as in a space station, then <br>
